VERDICT: APPROVED_WITH_COMMENTS
The diff successfully advances the Warm Ink migration on the targeted screens, but it is not a complete “across app” sweep yet.

Critical findings / analysis:
- `tailwind.config.ts` is correctly extended with a usable Warm Ink palette namespace (`wi.*`), enabling classes like `bg-wi-bg`, `text-wi-t1`, etc.
- In the changed page files, the previously called-out cold Tailwind utilities (`bg-white`, `bg-slate-*`, `text-slate-*`, `text-gray-*`, `border-gray-*`, `bg-gray-*`) were removed/replaced as expected.
- `not-found.tsx` now uses Warm Ink Tailwind classes (`bg-wi-bg`, `text-wi-t1`, `text-wi-t3`, `text-wi-primary`), which aligns with the task intent.
- However, a repo-wide scan still finds `bg-white` in reusable components (`client/src/components/GlowButton.tsx`, `SpringButton.tsx`, `components/premium/PetHeroCard.tsx`, `PremiumButton.tsx`). These components appear currently unused, so this is not a blocker for visible behavior on the 10 pages, but it means the sweep is not fully global.
- Minor architectural note: many replacements were done with inline hex/rgba styles rather than Tailwind aliases/tokens; functionally fine, but it weakens consistency and future theming leverage.

Security:
- None observed (no auth/input/secrets-risk changes in this diff).

Next actions:
1) Finish a true global sweep by replacing remaining `bg-white`/cold utilities in shared components, even if currently unused.
2) Normalize new warm colors toward Tailwind `wi.*` utilities (or shared CSS vars) instead of scattered inline literals.
3) Run a final automated class scan in `client/src/**/*.{tsx,ts}` to enforce no residual cold utility classes before merge.VERDICT: APPROVED_WITH_COMMENTS
